From: Gabi Falk <gabifalk@gmx.com>
Date: Sun, 7 Jun 2026 08:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] mips: forward seven arguments from the public syscall() on o32

The o32 ABI implements some syscalls that take 64-bit arguments as
seven-argument syscalls -- an explicit alignment pad followed by two
64-bit values, each split into a register/stack pair, plus a trailing
32-bit argument.  fadvise64_64 (reached via __NR_fadvise64 on o32) and
sync_file_range are the two such syscalls.

The generic Linux implementation of the public syscall() function
(sysdeps/unix/sysv/linux/syscall.c) only forwards six arguments, so the
seventh -- "advice" for fadvise64_64, "flags" for sync_file_range -- was
silently dropped and never reached the kernel.  glibc's own callers are
unaffected because they go through internal_syscall7, but applications
(and test suites such as strace's) that issue these syscalls through the
public syscall() interface received the wrong result.

Provide an o32 variant of syscall() that forwards seven arguments.  o32
already has internal_syscall7 (via __mips_syscall7); n32/n64 keep the
generic six-argument implementation as they have no seven-argument
syscalls.  As in the RISC-V variant the arguments are received as named
parameters rather than through <stdarg.h>: o32 va_arg over-aligns the
stack overflow area and would skip the first stack-resident argument.

Signed-off-by: Gabi Falk <gabifalk@gmx.com>
---
diff --git a/sysdeps/unix/sysv/linux/mips/mips32/syscall.c b/sysdeps/unix/sysv/linux/mips/mips32/syscall.c
new file mode 100644
index 0000000..fb0a612
--- /dev/null
+++ b/sysdeps/unix/sysv/linux/mips/mips32/syscall.c
@@ -0,0 +1,43 @@
+/* Indirect system call.  Linux/MIPS o32 version.
+   Copyright (C) 1997-2026 Free Software Foundation, Inc.
+   This file is part of the GNU C Library.
+
+   The GNU C Library is free software; you can redistribute it and/or
+   modify it under the terms of the GNU Lesser General Public
+   License as published by the Free Software Foundation; either
+   version 2.1 of the License, or (at your option) any later version.
+
+   The GNU C Library is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,
+   but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of
+   MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the GNU
+   Lesser General Public License for more details.
+
+   You should have received a copy of the GNU Lesser General Public
+   License along with the GNU C Library.  If not, see
+   <https://www.gnu.org/licenses/>.  */
+
+#include <sysdep.h>
+
+/* The o32 ABI implements some syscalls that take 64-bit arguments as
+   seven-argument syscalls (an explicit alignment pad plus two 64-bit
+   values split into register/stack pairs), namely fadvise64_64 and
+   sync_file_range.  The generic implementation only forwards six
+   arguments, so provide an o32 variant that forwards seven.
+
+   Like the RISC-V variant, the arguments are received as named
+   parameters rather than through <stdarg.h>: o32 va_arg over-aligns the
+   stack overflow area and would skip the first stack-resident argument,
+   which would corrupt the argument list of these very syscalls.  */
+
+long int
+syscall (long int number, long int a0, long int a1, long int a2,
+	 long int a3, long int a4, long int a5, long int a6)
+{
+  long int r = INTERNAL_SYSCALL_NCS_CALL (number, a0, a1, a2, a3, a4, a5, a6);
+  if (__glibc_unlikely (INTERNAL_SYSCALL_ERROR_P (r)))
+    {
+      __set_errno (-r);
+      return -1;
+    }
+  return r;
+}
